<span class="header1">COMMUNITY SERVICE</span>
<p>The occupations in this field are important. They provide
services to the community.  They often use technology to provide
these services. If you want to help your community and you like
technology, these may be good occupations for you.</p>

<hr size="1" />

	<span class="header2">Construction and Building
Inspector</span><br />
	<img class="job_pic" src="/images/icons/FG/43241.jpg"
width="100" height="100" border="0" alt="Building Inspector" />
	<span class="header3">Job Description</span>
	<blockquote>Building inspectors make sure that buildings are
safe.  They work on-site looking to see that builders follow safety
codes set by the government. As a building inspector, you would make
sure the building is built to stay strong. You might check, for
example, that the roof could not collapse under snow. Or, you might
make sure that there is an easy way to leave the building in case of
a fire.  You would check the building for flaws and insist they be
fixed.</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Education</span>
	<blockquote>More often employers look for persons who have
experience in construction and who have studied engineering or architecture. A degree from a community or junior college with courses in building inspection,
home inspection, construction technology, drafting, and mathematics is also desirable.
Many community colleges offer certification in building inspection 
technology. </blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Salary</span>
	<blockquote>The median annual wage of building inspectors
was $60,710 in May 2019. </blockquote>

<hr size="1" />

	<span class="header2">Land Surveyor</span><br />
	<img class="job_pic" src="/images/icons/FG/43169.jpg"
width="100" height="100" border="0" alt="Land Surveyor" />
	<span class="header3">Job Description</span>
	<blockquote>Surveyors establish official land, airspace, and
water boundaries. They write descriptions of land for deeds, leases,
and other legal documents; define airspace for airports; and take
measurements of construction and mineral sites. Surveyors provide
data about the shape, contour, location, elevation, or dimension of
land or land features.</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Education</span>
	<blockquote>Most surveyors need a bachelor's degree. A
number of universities offer bachelor's degree programs in
surveying and many community colleges, technical institutes, and
vocational schools offer one, two, and three-year programs in
surveying or surveying technology. </blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Salary</span>
	<blockquote>The median annual wage of land surveyors was
$63,420 in May 2019. </blockquote>

<hr size="1" />

	<span class="header2">Firefighter</span><br />
	<img class="job_pic" src="/images/icons/FG/1392.jpg"
width="100" height="100" border="0" alt="Firefighter" />
	<span class="header3">Job Description</span>
	<blockquote>Firefighters control and put out fires that
threaten lives or property.  As a firefighter, you would have to act
quickly and responsibly in the middle of a fire or other emergency.
You would also learn CPR and first aid so that you could help
injured people. Fire fighting is dangerous and
unpredictable.</blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Education</span>
	<blockquote>Most fire fighters have a high school diploma;
however, the completion of community college courses, or in some
cases an associate degree in fire science, may improve an
applicant's chances for a job. Firefighters are usually trained at a fire academy and must pass physical and written tests. They must also earn emergency medical technician (EMT) certification. </blockquote>
	<span class="header3">Salary</span>
	<blockquote>The median annual wage of firefighters was
$50,850 in May 2019. </blockquote>

